I&#039;ve been using a standing desk for about two years now.  Prior to that, I tried *and failed* a few times.  The things that lead me to succeed:&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
1. The height of the desk needs to be perfect.  If your wrists feel any sort of pain after a day at your desk, the height is off by as little as an inch.&lt;br /&gt;
&lt;br /&gt;
2. You need a padded mat to stand on.  It substantially reduces the fatigue on your feet and back.  I couldn&#039;t stand all day until I got one, but now I&#039;m totally comfortable.  I purchased http://www.amazon.com/Sublime-Imprint-Anti-Fatigue-Nantucket-Cinnamon/dp/B003BYRDK2/ref=sr_1_2?ie=UTF8&#038;qid=1349627923&#038;sr=8-2&#038;keywords=standing+pad and it worked out well for me.

